docs.lead_paragraph: MORTALITY.--The Health Officer reports 97 deaths as the total for the week ending Saturday last. They are classified as follows: Men, 14; women--; boys, 26; girls, 31; adults, 40; children, 59; males, 42; females, 55; colored persons, 2; 20, or about one-fifth of the whole, were more than 50 years old, and 58, or about three-fifths, were under 21 years of age; one at least died of old age; 71 were natives.

docs.lead_paragraph: A THRICE-TOLD TALE.-The sailing of a California steamer from this port on Monday next is producing its usual effects upon our Police Courts, in the shape of complaints against those everlasting ticket-swindling concerns which have disgraced the City for years, but which our authorities continue to show their inability or their disinclination to suppress.

docs.lead_paragraph: One of our cotemporaries has called the attention of the public to the fact that a number of Italian exiles, the victims of King BOMBA'S brutal tyranny, are now on their way to our shores, and will shortly land in this port, and expresses the hope that New-York will give them a reception worthy of the extent of their sufferings, and the cause in which those sufferings have been endured.

docs.lead_paragraph: It will be remembered that on the 20th of July last, Mrs. JOHN M. BRANNAN, wife of Captain BRANNAN, of the U. S. Army, mysteriously disappeared. Her husband was then at Key West, Florida, on duty, and MIS. BRANNAN was residing with her mother, the widow of Col. CRANE, of the U. s. Army, at Chelsea, Staten Island.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Royal mail steamship America, Captain MILLAR, from Liverpool 3 P. M. of the 29th ult., arrived at Halifax at 10.30 P. M. of the 14th inst. The America har experienced a succession of strong westerly gales during the entire voyage. The steamship City of Manchester, from New-York, arrived at Liverpool at 3 o'clock on the morning of Jan. 28.
